## Purpose

This document tells the team what to expect from working at **{{COMPANY_NAME}}**, and what the company expects from them in return. It complements — and does not replace — the individual *Employment Contract*.

Where this document and the *Employment Contract* disagree, the *Employment Contract* wins. Where the *Employment Contract* is silent, this document is the answer.

## Working pattern

The standard working week is 37.5 hours, Monday to Friday, with core hours **{{TODO_CORE_HOURS}}**. Outside core hours team members work as suits them, provided their commitments to the rest of the team are met.

We are a remote-first company. There is no requirement to attend an office unless a specific event (offsite, hiring day, customer onsite) requires it. Where an office attendance is requested the company covers reasonable travel costs.

## Holiday

Full-time employees are entitled to **{{TODO_HOLIDAY_DAYS}}** days of paid holiday per year, plus the eight UK bank holidays. Holiday is requested via the system named in the *Tool Stack Register*; the line manager approves it.

Unused holiday up to **five days** can be carried over to the next year by agreement with the line manager. Holiday in excess of this is forfeited. On leaving the company, accrued and unused holiday is paid out in the final salary payment.

## Sickness and other absences

If you cannot work because you are unwell, tell your line manager as early in the day as you can. There is no need to provide a reason beyond "I am unwell"; the company trusts the team to be honest.

Absences of more than seven consecutive days require a fit note from a GP. Statutory Sick Pay applies after the standard waiting period; the company tops it up to full salary for the first **{{TODO_SICK_PAY_WEEKS}}** weeks of any rolling twelve-month period.

## Expenses

Business expenses are reimbursed within 30 days of submission. Submit receipts via the system named in the *Tool Stack Register* and attach the business reason. Expenses must be reasonable, evidenced and incurred in the course of company business.

Specific limits and pre-approval thresholds are recorded in the *Expense Policy*. If in doubt, ask the finance owner before you spend.

## Conduct

We expect every member of the team to act with integrity, to treat colleagues and customers with respect, and to protect confidential information.

Conduct that falls short of these expectations is dealt with under the *Disciplinary Policy*. Serious misconduct — fraud, harassment, breach of the *IP Assignment Agreement* — may result in summary dismissal without notice.

## Raising a concern

If you have a concern about how you have been treated, or about anything else at work, raise it with your line manager in the first instance. If that is not appropriate, or you have raised it and the issue has not been resolved, the *Grievance Policy* sets out the formal route.

Concerns about unlawful conduct, fraud, or public-interest matters can also be raised under the *Whistleblowing Policy*; that route protects you from retaliation.

## Leaving the company

When an engagement comes to an end — by resignation, by mutual agreement, or by the company giving notice — the *Offboarding Checklist* takes over. It covers handover, access removal, return of equipment, and final payment.

The terms of departure are governed by the *Employment Contract*. Notice periods are recorded there; statutory minima always apply.

## Remote-first norms

We are remote-first. That means:

- **Default to async.** Any decision that does not require a real-time conversation gets typed up first.
- **Write things down.** A conversation that is not written down is a conversation that did not happen, as far as the rest of the team is concerned.
- **Respect time zones.** Meetings that include people in two or more zones are scheduled in the overlap, not in someone's evening.
- **Camera on for important conversations.** A 1:1, a difficult feedback conversation, an interview — these are not voice-only.
- **Camera off for routine conversations.** A standup, a quick "have you got five minutes" — these are voice-only by default.

The headline: written first, async first, camera on when it matters.

## Communication channels

- **Email.** Outside the company. Signed off by a director for anything contractual.
- **Team chat.** Inside the company. Default channel for anything routine.
- **DMs.** For one-to-one conversations that genuinely need privacy; everything else goes in a channel so others can learn from it.
- **Video calls.** For the conversations the chat or email cannot carry — interviews, hard feedback, customer escalations.
- **Tickets.** For work that has a clear definition of done; nothing important should be tracked only in chat.

The principle: choose the channel that gives the conversation the right level of permanence and the right audience.

## Legal compliance

We comply with the laws of every country in which we operate. Where the laws of two countries conflict, we comply with the stricter and document the reason in the *Decision Log*.

We do not interpret the law informally. Where a question has legal consequence — a contract, a privacy decision, an employment matter — we take advice from a qualified professional. The cost of advice is recorded in the budget; the absence of advice is recorded as a risk.

